video.title: Flavorful Origins
video.synopsis: Embark on a delightful journey through the culinary traditions of China and uncover the stories of the people who create and cherish its dishes.

episodes.synopsis: In Jiayuguan city, mutton tallow envelops lamb skewers with layers of flavor. In the Ganjia pastures, herders cook lamb with tripe using hot stones.
episodes.title: Mutton

episodes.synopsis: Baked, steamed or stir-fried, the root of the lily plant is sweet and aromatic. Its flower also serves as a salad ingredient or a noodle topping.
episodes.title: Lily

episodes.synopsis: From Linxia to the Hexi Corridor, sheep offal can be found sizzling on hot plates, stuffed into casings and wrapped in caul fat.
episodes.title: Cooked chopped entrails of sheep

episodes.synopsis: In Wuwei County, watermelon farmers enjoy flaxseed rolls as a dry staple food. Flaxseed oil also infuses pastries like Yongdeng mooncake with aroma.
episodes.title: Flaxseed

episodes.synopsis: Grown in the Longdong plateaus, buckwheat can be made into jelly noodles, pancake batter and Tianshui guagua, a savory breakfast dish.
episodes.title: Gua Gua

episodes.synopsis: A slow-cooked beef broth is the soul of the hand-pulled Lanzhou beef noodle, a go-to dish for discerning eaters searching for a taste of home.
episodes.title: Beef noodles

episodes.synopsis: Baked, air-dried or sliced into strips, the absorbent wheat gluten can be added to soups and meaty stews, making it a perfect flavor reservoir.
episodes.title: Gluten

episodes.synopsis: Found in mullet roe and hot pot, souherb is a white soupy ingredient made by fermenting vegetables like endive, celery, carrot or cabbage.
episodes.title: Souherb

episodes.synopsis: From Lanzhou to Wuwei, epicures put a different spin on niang pi, a glutenous cold noodle dish that often comes with sesame, cucumber and chili oil.
episodes.title: Niang Pi

episodes.synopsis: Dingxi boasts more than 30 varieties of potato, eaten sliced, mashed or made in the form of noodles cooked with pork or spicy sauces.
episodes.title: Potato

episodes.synopsis: Yunnan is known for a variety of dairy products, including Dali rushan: thinly sliced cheese that can be fried, grilled or dipped in honey.
episodes.title: Dairy Products

episodes.synopsis: A local wild berry features in nanpie, which refers to different types of flavorful pastes made from mashed vegetables or fish.
episodes.title: Nan Piě

episodes.synopsis: Sa is a culinary tradition that pairs cold meat or raw vegetables with a versatile sauce that is often mixed with pig blood curd.
episodes.title: Sa Piě

episodes.synopsis: Derived from the fruits of the Chinese lacquer tree, qiyou is an oil used to cook eggs, congee,  pork stew, roast chicken and even bee larvae.
episodes.title: Lacquer Seed Oil

episodes.synopsis: Found in local moon cake fillings, Xuanwei cured ham can be thinly sliced, steamed, cooked with egg, stewed or served as cold cuts.
episodes.title: Ham

episodes.synopsis: Salted and partially dried, the sow thistle can be pickled and stir-fried with pork to lend a sour, crunchy flavor, or added to white radish stew.
episodes.title: Pickled Vegetables

episodes.synopsis: Wrapped in leaves with sticky rice or spiced fish, the Musa basjoo -- a banana found in Yunnan -- can make for a sweet snack or a savory dish.
episodes.title: Hardy Banana

episodes.synopsis: Besides being an appetite stimulant, tart fruits like lemon and sour papaya can be added to shredded chicken, carp or a sauce for dousing live shrimp.
episodes.title: Sour Fruits

episodes.synopsis: The er, a flattened rice flour cake, can be baked into a sticky snack, sliced and stir-fried with vegetables or julienned into noodle-like strands.
episodes.title: Rice Cake

episodes.synopsis: Zha, an old custom, is an assortment of dried fermented vegetables or fish served as side dishes, made with ancient methods of food preservation.
episodes.title: Salted Flour

episodes.synopsis: In Chaoshan, olives are preserved in distinct ways and appear in a variety of dishes, including fresh juices and meat soups.
episodes.title: Olives

episodes.synopsis: A quintessentially Chaoshan staple and a taste of home for many, kway teow (rice-noodle strips) can be stir-fried or wrapped around tasty fillings.
episodes.title: Hu Tieu

episodes.synopsis: Garlic. Cilantro. Chili pepper. The marinated raw-crab dish varies in style from Puning to Shantou, but it's always fresh and tender.
episodes.title: Marinated Crab

episodes.synopsis: Cinnamon, anise and galangal are among the spices that go into Chaoshan brine, a key ingredient in braised offal, goose head and hot pot.
episodes.title: Brine

episodes.synopsis: Long ago, migrants from the north brought soybeans to Chaoshan, now home to a unique bean paste featured in many dishes, from spinach to steamed fish.
episodes.title: Puning Bean Paste

episodes.synopsis: An age-old Chaoshan tradition, the preserved white radish can put an innovative spin on various dishes, from spare ribs to stir-fried squid.
episodes.title: Preserved Radish

episodes.synopsis: To bring out umami and impart the flavor of the sea, the versatile ingredient seaweed can be stir-fried, deep-fried, roasted and sprinkled on soup.
episodes.title: Seaweed

episodes.synopsis: Steamed, marinated, stir-fried, grilled or dried. A classic in Chaoshan cuisine, the oyster is traditionally cultivated in the town of Jingzhou.
episodes.title: Oysters

episodes.synopsis: A regional product, the Chaozhou orange can be deep-fried or dried and preserved to make sweet treats, while its peel can be used for zesty seasoning.
episodes.title: Chaozhou Mandarin Oranges

episodes.synopsis: In the Hakka tradition, tea leaves are cooked with fresh herbs, then ground with sesame seeds or peanuts in a mortar to make lei cha, a fragrant drink.
episodes.title: Lei Cha

episodes.synopsis: Garlic, fat, liquor and fermented bean curd. The traditional tofu cake is a baked pastry boasting a rich taste profile and centuries of history.
episodes.title: Tofu Cake

episodes.synopsis: Expert butchers in Chaoshan sharpen their knives to slice premium beef into perfect, marbled cutlets that are juicy, tender, and ready for hot pot.
episodes.title: Beef Hot Pot

episodes.synopsis: Inheriting the techniques of previous generations, makers of Chaoshan beef meatballs dedicate hours of hard work to achieve perfect texture and flavor.
episodes.title: Beef Meatballs

episodes.synopsis: Enjoyed with vegetables and dipping sauce, yu sheng (freshly sliced raw fish) is a delicacy with a long history in Chaoshan.
episodes.title: Yusheng

episodes.synopsis: Salted, boiled and air-dried in bamboo baskets, the mackerel scad is among many seafoods that make for a chewy, flavorful and simple main dish.
episodes.title: Meal of Fish

episodes.synopsis: Indispensable to Chaoshan cooking, fish sauce is traditionally made by salt-curing and fermenting hilsa herring, but new methods have cropped up.
episodes.title: Fish Sauce

episodes.synopsis: In Chaoshan, the lizardfish is deboned and pounded to make surimi (fish paste) -- a versatile ingredient with a uniquely smooth and elastic texture.
episodes.title: Fish Ball and Wrapped Fish

episodes.synopsis: Harvested from Nan'ao Island's shores, mussels are a summer delicacy that can be cooked with basil, folded into spring rolls and added to fried rice.
episodes.title: Mussels

episodes.synopsis: Galangal arrived in Chaoshan from Southeast Asia a long time ago, imbuing meat dishes like chicken and lamb with a fragrant punch.
episodes.title: Galangal

episodes.synopsis: Known for both taste and nutritional value, Chinese motherwort is blanched and added to soup and congee as a breakfast favorite.
episodes.title: Chinese Motherwort
